JavaScript is a dynamically typed language, which means that variables do not have any specific type until they are assigned a value. This can make it difficult to identify and fix errors in code, as well as to ensure that variables are being used correctly.
TypeScript is a statically typed language that is built on top of JavaScript. It adds optional type annotations to JavaScript code, which allow the compiler to catch errors and ensure that variables are being used correctly. This makes it easier to write bug-free code and to catch errors before they become issues in production.
Type assertions are a feature of TypeScript that allow developers to specify the type of a variable or function parameter at runtime. This is useful in cases where the type of a variable may not be immediately obvious to the compiler, such as when a variable is being passed as a parameter to a function.
Here is an example of how to use a type assertion to specify that a variable will have a specific type, even when multiple types are theoretically possible:
```
